The Importance of Breast Cancer Risk Awareness

Nicole Ayala

2023-05-01

The Purpose of This Independent Project

  • To focus on some factors that correlate to the cause of breast cancer that then impact the possibility of the cancer recurring due to said factors.
  • To investigate how these factors associate with each other.

Questions to Answer

  • How do the quantitative variables matter when it comes to determining breast cancer malignancy?
  • Does age have a huge affect when it comes to severity of malignancy and recurrence probability?
  • What particular section of the breast is most likely to be diagnosed with cancer with a large tumor?
  • Are middle aged individuals more common to undergo irradiation therapy compared to those 50 and older?

Read in the Data

cancer <- read_csv(here("Independent Project", "Data", "breast-cancer.csv")) # the breast cancer data set
breastcancer <- read_csv(here("Independent Project", "Data","data.csv")) 
#View(breastcancer)

Filter the Data

hexcancer <- cancer %>% # piping cancer dataset to hexcancer 
  drop_na() %>% # remove any unnecessary na's
  filter(class == "recurrence-events") # only include recurrence event for class (those that had the cancer come back)

barcancer <- cancer %>% # piping cancer dataset to barcancer
  drop_na() # remove any unnecessary na's

heatcancer <- breastcancer %>% # piping cancer dataset to heatcancer
  filter(diagnosis == "M") %>% # only include malignant tumor  cancer diagnoses
  filter(symmetry_mean >= ".25") # want to have percentages higher than 25% as those represent higher breast density fatty tissue rates of 3 and 4

Tabyl

heatcancer %>%
  tabyl(diagnosis,symmetry_mean, show_missing_levels = FALSE) %>% # There are only 2 categories:diagnosis,symmetry mean; diagnosis has been filtered out to only show Malignant, , don't want any NAs or missing data points 
  adorn_totals("row") %>% # it can be by column, by row, or both - one of "row", "col", or c("row", "col")
  adorn_percentages("row") %>% # it can be by column, by row, or all
  adorn_pct_formatting(digits = 1) %>% # how many numbers after the decimal in the percentage
  adorn_ns("rear")%>% # can be moved to the front or the back of the percentage, shows you how many times that diagnosis was brought up at those gray scale values
  adorn_title(placement = "top", row_name = "Diagnosis", col_name = "Symmetry Average and Texture Average") # changes the name of your row and column names

HeatMap

This figure shows the averages of texture sensitivity of the breast from the center point of the core tumor based on their average radii, organized by the diagnosis of a benign or malignant tumor.

How do the quantitative variables matter when it comes to determining breast cancer malignancy?

According to the figure above, these quantitative variables, specifically here average of both breast radii and texture demonstrate that individuals who tend to have higher radii(the average total of distance from the areola to the primary site of where the cancer was discovered) is more likely to have a higher texture (measures standard deviation of the gray scale values of the imaging done) so if there were some abnormal benign or malignant micro/macrocalcifications, (excessive white fatty breast tissue) it would most likely be malignant if both average texture and mean were above the average. In a normal mammogram, normal fatty tissue would be all dark with little streaks of dense white fatty tissue, but here its not the usual case.

### Bubble Plot

This bubble plot demonstrates how older breast cancer patients (aged 50+) tend to commonly get tumors on the bottom left breast with a malignancy degree of 3.

What particular section of the breast is most likely to be diagnosed with cancer with a large tumor?

Bubble Class Plot

In this figure,older breast cancer patients in the age range of 70-79 usually do not survive with severe malignant tumors, and for most of the individuals before that certain age, usually do not have a recurrence of the cancer coming back, avoiding remission.

Does age have a huge affect when it comes to severity of malignancy and recurrence probability?

Through the animation going by age showing the various degrees of malignancy

Bar Plot

This animated figure illustrates the age of patients at the time of their diagnosis who have undergone a specific type of chemo therapy known as irradiation therapy which is more invasive and weakening.

Are middle aged individuals more common to undergo irradiation therapy compared to those 50 and older?
